# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aliphatic-compound
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aliphatic-compound/1-2-butadiene] The C4-fraction of petroleum obtained by cracking and separated by distillation consists of many compounds, predominantly (75%) 1,3-butadiene, isobutene, and 1-butene.
[src:aliphatic-compound/1-2-butadiene] 1,2‑Butadiene comprises less than 1% of this mixture.
[src:aliphatic-compound/1-2-butadiene] It is partially purified by extraction with *N*-methylpyrrolidone.
[src:aliphatic-compound/1-butene] Polymerization of 1-butene gives polybutylene, which is used to make piping for domestic plumbing.
[src:aliphatic-compound/1-butene] Another application is as a comonomer in the production of certain kinds of polyethylene, such as linear low-density polyethylene (LLDPE).
[src:aliphatic-compound/1-butene] It has also been used as a precursor to polypropylene resins, butylene oxide, and butanone.
[src:aliphatic-compound/1-butene] 1-Butene is produced by separation from crude C4 refinery streams and by ethylene dimerization.
[src:aliphatic-compound/1-butene] The former affords a mixture of 1-and 2-butenes, while the latter affords only the terminal alkene.
[src:aliphatic-compound/1-butene] It is distilled to give a very high purity product.
[src:aliphatic-compound/1-butene] An estimated 12 billion kilograms were produced in 2011.
[src:aliphatic-compound/1-butyne] 1-Butyne participates in reactions typical for terminal alkynes, such as alkyne metathesis, hydrogenation, condensation with formaldehyde.
[src:aliphatic-compound/1-butyne] Based on its heat of combustion, it is slightly more stable than its isomer 2-butyne.
[src:aliphatic-compound/1-butyne] The combustion of 1-Butyne produces propargyl radicals, a precursor to soot and polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons, as the propargyl radicals can form basic aromatic rings, making butyne's fuel usage a concern for emissions.
[src:aliphatic-compound/1-butyne] 1-Butyne is in unsaturated C4 petroleum cuts, and has to be separated out in industrial hydrorefining to make 1-butene, which is used to make low density polyethylene and polybutene.
[src:aliphatic-compound/1-butyne] Distillation is impractical due to similar boiling points, so 1-butyne is removed by catalytic hydrogenation.
[src:aliphatic-compound/1-butyne] Usually the catalyst is palladium, operated with liquid hydrocarbon and hydrogen gas at 20-60°C and pressures up to 10 bar.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] As an alkyne, acetylene is unsaturated because its two carbon atoms are bonded together in a triple bond.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] The carbon–carbon triple bond places all four atoms in the same straight line, with CCH bond angles of 180°.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] The triple bond in acetylene results in a high energy content that is released when acetylene is burned.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Acetylene was discovered in 1836 by Edmund Davy, who identified it as a "new carburet of hydrogen".
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] It was an accidental discovery while attempting to isolate potassium metal.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] By heating potassium carbonate with carbon at very high temperatures, he produced a residue of what is now known as potassium carbide, (K2C2), which reacted with water to release the new gas.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] It was rediscovered in 1860 by French chemist Marcellin Berthelot, who coined the name *acétylène*.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Berthelot's empirical formula for acetylene (C4H2), as well as the alternative name "*quadricarbure d'hydrogène*" (hydrogen quadricarbide), were incorrect because many chemists at that time used the wrong atomic mass for carbon (6 instead of 12).
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Berthelot was able to prepare this gas by passing vapours of organic compounds (methanol, ethanol, etc.) through a red hot tube and collecting the effluent.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] He also found that acetylene was formed by sparking electricity through mixed cyanogen and hydrogen gases.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Berthelot later obtained acetylene directly by passing hydrogen between the poles of a carbon arc.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] It is a recovered side product in production of ethylene by cracking of hydrocarbons.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Approximately 400,000 tonnes were produced by this method in 1983.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Its presence in ethylene is usually undesirable because of its explosive character and its ability to poison Ziegler–Natta catalysts.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] It is selectively hydrogenated into ethylene, usually using Pd–Ag catalysts.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] This last reaction is implemented in the process of anaerobic decomposition of methane by microwave plasma.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] The first sample of acetylene produced was by Edmund Davy in 1836, via hydrolysis (decomposition using water) of potassium carbide.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] This reaction was discovered by Friedrich Wöhler in 1862, but a suitable commercial scale production method which allowed acetylene to be put into wider scale use was not found until 1892 by the Canadian inventor Thomas Willson while searching for a viable commercial production method for aluminum.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] As late as the early 21st century, China, Japan, and Eastern Europe produced acetylene primarily by this method.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] The use of this technology has since declined worldwide with the notable exception of China, with its emphasis on coal-based chemical industry, as of 2013.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Otherwise oil has increasingly supplanted coal as the chief source of reduced carbon.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Calcium carbide production requires high temperatures, ~2000 °C, necessitating the use of an electric arc furnace.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] In the US, this process was an important part of the late-19th century revolution in chemistry enabled by the massive hydroelectric power project at Niagara Falls.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] In terms of valence bond theory, in each carbon atom the 2s orbital hybridizes with one 2p orbital thus forming an sp hybrid.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] The other two 2p orbitals remain unhybridized.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] The two ends of the two sp hybrid orbital overlap to form a strong σ valence bond between the carbons, while on each of the other two ends hydrogen atoms attach also by σ bonds.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] The two unchanged 2p orbitals form a pair of weaker π bonds.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Since acetylene is a linear symmetrical molecule, it possesses the D∞h point group.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] At atmospheric pressure, acetylene cannot exist as a liquid and does not have a melting point.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] The triple point on the phase diagram corresponds to the melting point (−80.8 °C) at the minimal pressure at which liquid acetylene can exist (1.27 atm).
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] At temperatures below the triple point, solid acetylene can change directly to the vapour (gas) by sublimation.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] The sublimation point at atmospheric pressure is −84.0 °C.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] At room temperature and atmospheric pressure, the solubility of acetylene in acetone is 27.9 g per kg.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] For the same amount of dimethylformamide (DMF), the solubility is 51 g.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] At 20.26 bar, the solubility increases to 689.0 and 628.0 g for acetone and DMF, respectively.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] These solvents are used in pressurized gas cylinders.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Approximately 20% of acetylene is supplied by the industrial gases industry for oxyacetylene gas welding and cutting due to the high temperature of the flame.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Combustion of acetylene with oxygen produces a flame of over 3,600 K (3,330 °C; 6,020 °F), releasing 11.8 kJ/g.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Oxygen with acetylene is the hottest burning common gas mixture.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Oxy-acetylene welding was a popular welding process in previous decades.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] The development and advantages of arc-based welding processes have made oxy-fuel welding nearly extinct for many applications.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Acetylene usage for welding has dropped significantly.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Bell Canada cable-repair technicians still use portable acetylene-fuelled torch kits as a soldering tool for sealing lead sleeve splices in manholes and in some aerial locations.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Oxyacetylene welding may also be used in areas where electricity is not readily accessible.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Oxyacetylene cutting is used in many metal fabrication shops.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] For use in welding and cutting, the working pressures must be controlled by a regulator, since above 15 psi (100 kPa), if subjected to a shockwave (caused, for example, by a flashback), acetylene decomposes explosively into hydrogen and carbon.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Acetylene is useful for many processes, but few are conducted on a commercial scale.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] One of the major chemical applications is ethynylation of formaldehyde.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] The reaction gives butynediol, with propargyl alcohol as the by-product.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Copper acetylide is used as the catalyst.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] In addition to ethynylation, acetylene reacts with carbon monoxide to give acrylic acid, or acrylic esters.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] These derivatives form products such as acrylic fibers, glasses, paints, resins, and polymers.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Except in China, use of acetylene as a chemical feedstock has declined by 70% from 1965 to 2007 owing to cost and environmental considerations.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] In China, acetylene is a major precursor to vinyl chloride.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Prior to the widespread use of petrochemicals, coal-derived acetylene was a building block for several industrial chemicals.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Thus acetylene can be hydrated to give acetaldehyde, which in turn can be oxidized to acetic acid.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Processes leading to acrylates were also commercialized.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Almost all of these processes became obsolete with the availability of petroleum-derived ethylene and propylene.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] In 1881, the Russian chemist Mikhail Kucherov described the hydration of acetylene to acetaldehyde using catalysts such as mercury(II) bromide.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Before the advent of the Wacker process, this reaction was conducted on an industrial scale.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] The polymerization of acetylene with Ziegler–Natta catalysts produces polyacetylene films.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Polyacetylene, a chain of CH centres with alternating single and double bonds, was one of the first discovered organic semiconductors.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Its reaction with iodine produces a highly electrically conducting material.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Although such materials are not useful, these discoveries led to the developments of organic semiconductors, as recognized by the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 2000 to Alan J.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Heeger, Alan G MacDiarmid, and Hideki Shirakawa.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] In the 1920s, pure acetylene was experimentally used as an inhalation anesthetic.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Acetylene is sometimes used for carburization (that is, hardening) of steel when the object is too large to fit into a furnace.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Acetylene is used to volatilize carbon in radiocarbon dating.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] The carbonaceous material in an archeological sample is treated with lithium metal in a small specialized research furnace to form lithium carbide (also known as lithium acetylide).
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] The carbide can then be reacted with water, as usual, to form acetylene gas to feed into a mass spectrometer to measure the isotopic ratio of carbon-14 to carbon-12.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Acetylene combustion produces a strong, bright light and the ubiquity of carbide lamps drove much acetylene commercialization in the early 20th century.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Common applications included coastal lighthouses, street lights, and automobile and mining headlamps.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] In most of these applications, direct combustion is a fire hazard, and so acetylene has been replaced, first by incandescent lighting and many years later by low-power/high-lumen LEDs.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Nevertheless, acetylene lamps remain in limited use in remote or otherwise inaccessible areas and in countries with a weak or unreliable central electric grid.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] The energy richness of the C≡C triple bond and the rather high solubility of acetylene in water make it a suitable substrate for bacteria, provided an adequate source is available.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] A number of bacteria living on acetylene have been identified.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Acetylene is a moderately common chemical in the universe, often associated with the atmospheres of gas giants.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] One curious discovery of acetylene is on Enceladus, a moon of Saturn.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Natural acetylene is believed to form from catalytic decomposition of long-chain hydrocarbons at temperatures of 1,700 K (1,430 °C; 2,600 °F) and above.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Since such temperatures are highly unlikely on such a small distant body, this discovery is potentially suggestive of catalytic reactions within that moon, making it a promising site to search for prebiotic chemistry.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] In vinylation reactions, H−X compounds add across the triple bond.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Alcohols and phenols add to acetylene to give vinyl ethers.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Similarly, vinylpyrrolidone and vinylcarbazole are produced industrially by vinylation of 2-pyrrolidone and carbazole.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] The hydration of acetylene is a vinylation reaction, but the resulting vinyl alcohol isomerizes to acetaldehyde.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] The reaction is catalyzed by mercury salts.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] This reaction once was the dominant technology for acetaldehyde production, but it has been displaced by the Wacker process, which affords acetaldehyde by oxidation of ethylene, a cheaper feedstock.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] A similar situation applies to the conversion of acetylene to the valuable vinyl chloride by hydrochlorination versus the oxychlorination of ethylene.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Vinyl acetate is used instead of acetylene for some vinylations, which are more accurately described as transvinylations.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Higher esters of vinyl acetate have been used in the synthesis of vinyl formate.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Acetylene and its derivatives (2-butyne, diphenylacetylene, etc.) form complexes with transition metals.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Its bonding to the metal is somewhat similar to that of ethylene complexes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Metal acetylides, species of the formula L*n*M−C2R, are also common.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Copper(I) acetylide and silver acetylide can be formed in aqueous solutions with ease due to a favorable solubility equilibrium.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Various organometallic and inorganic reagents are effective.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Acetylene can be semihydrogenated to ethylene, providing a feedstock for a variety of polyethylene plastics.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Acetylene is not especially toxic, but when generated from calcium carbide, or CaC2, it can contain toxic impurities such as traces of phosphine and arsine, which gives it a distinct garlic-like smell.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] It is also highly flammable, as are most light hydrocarbons, hence its use in welding.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Although it is stable at normal pressures and temperatures, if it is subjected to pressures as low as 15 psig it can explode.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] The safe limit for acetylene therefore is 101 kPagage, or 15 psig.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Additionally, if acetylene is initiated by intense heat or a shockwave, it can decompose explosively if the absolute pressure of the gas exceeds about 200 kilopascals (29 psi).
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] It is therefore supplied and stored dissolved in acetone or dimethylformamide (DMF), contained in a gas cylinder with a porous filling, which renders it safe to transport and use, given proper handling.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Acetylene cylinders should be used in the upright position to avoid withdrawing acetone during use.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Information on safe storage of acetylene in upright cylinders is provided by the OSHA, Compressed Gas Association, United States Mine Safety and Health Administration (MSHA), EIGA, and other agencies.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Copper catalyses the decomposition of acetylene, and as a result acetylene should not be transported in copper pipes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Cylinders should be stored in an area segregated from oxidizers to avoid exacerbated reaction in case of fire/leakage.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Acetylene cylinders should not be stored in confined spaces, enclosed vehicles, garages, and buildings, to avoid unintended leakage leading to explosive atmosphere.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] In the US, National Electric Code (NEC) requires consideration for hazardous areas including those where acetylene may be released during accidents or leaks.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Consideration may include electrical classification and use of listed Group A electrical components in US.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] Further information on determining the areas requiring special consideration is in NFPA 497.
[src:aliphatic-compound/acetylene] In Europe, ATEX also requires consideration for hazardous areas where flammable gases may be released during accidents or leaks.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] In chemistry, **amines** (/əˈmiːn, ˈæmiːn/, UK also /ˈeɪmiːn/) are organic compounds that contain carbon–nitrogen bonds.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Amines are formed when one or more hydrogen atoms in ammonia are replaced by alkyl or aryl groups.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] The nitrogen atom in an amine possesses a lone pair of electrons.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Amines can also exist as heterocyclic compounds.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Aniline ( ${\ce {C6H7N}}$ ) is the simplest aromatic amine, consisting of a benzene ring bonded to an amino ( ${\ce {-NH2}}$ ) group.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Amines are classified into three types: primary (1°), secondary (2°), and tertiary (3°) amines.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] **Primary amines** (1°) contain one alkyl or aryl substituent and have the general formula ${\ce {RNH2}}$ .
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] **Secondary amines** (2°) have two alkyl or aryl groups attached to the nitrogen atom, with the general formula ${\ce {R2NH}}$ .
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] **Tertiary amines** (3°) contain three substituent groups bonded to the nitrogen atom, and are represented by the formula ${\ce {R3N}}$ .
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] The functional group −NH2 present in primary amines is called the amino group.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Amines can be classified according to the nature and number of substituents on nitrogen.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] **Aliphatic amines** contain only H and alkyl substituents.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] **Aromatic amines** have the nitrogen atom connected to an aromatic ring.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Compounds where the nitrogen atom is attached to a carbonyl group, thus having the structure R−C(=O)−NR′R″, are called amides.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Compounds containing four organic substituents on the nitrogen, thus having the structure R4N+X−, are quaternary ammonium salts.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Many kinds of anions are found in such compounds.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Typically, the compound is given the prefix "amino-" or the suffix "-amine".
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] The prefix "*N*-" shows substitution on the nitrogen atom.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] An organic compound with multiple amino groups is called a diamine, triamine, tetraamine and so forth.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Lower amines are named with the suffix *-amine*.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Higher amines have the prefix *amino* as a functional group.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] IUPAC however does not recommend this convention, but prefers the alkanamine form, e.g. butan-2-amine.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Hydrogen bonding significantly influences the properties of primary and secondary amines.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] For example, methyl and ethyl amines are gases under standard conditions, whereas the corresponding methyl and ethyl alcohols are liquids.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Amines possess a characteristic ammonia smell, liquid amines have a distinctive "fishy" and foul smell.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] The nitrogen atom features a lone electron pair that can bind H+ to form an ammonium ion R3NH+.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] The lone electron pair is represented in this article by two dots above or next to the N.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] The water solubility of simple amines is enhanced by hydrogen bonding involving these lone electron pairs.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Typically salts of ammonium compounds exhibit the following order of solubility in water: primary ammonium (RNH+3) > secondary ammonium (R2NH+2) > tertiary ammonium (R3NH+).
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Small aliphatic amines display significant solubility in many solvents, whereas those with large substituents are lipophilic.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Aromatic amines, such as aniline, have their lone pair electrons conjugated into the benzene ring, thus their tendency to engage in hydrogen bonding is diminished.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Their boiling points are high and their solubility in water is low.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Typically the presence of an amine functional group is deduced by a combination of techniques, including mass spectrometry as well as NMR and IR spectroscopies.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] 1H NMR signals for amines disappear upon treatment of the sample with D2O.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] In their infrared spectrum primary amines exhibit two N–H bands, whereas secondary amines exhibit only one.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] In their IR spectra, primary and secondary amines exhibit distinctive N–H stretching bands near 3300 cm−1.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Somewhat less distinctive are the bands appearing below 1600 cm−1, which are weaker and overlap with C–C and C–H modes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] For the case of propyl amine, the H–N–H scissor mode appears near 1600 cm−1, the C–N stretch near 1000 cm−1, and the R2N–H bend near 810 cm−1.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Alkyl amines characteristically feature tetrahedral nitrogen centers.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] C-N distances are slightly shorter than C-C distances.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] The energy barrier for the nitrogen inversion of the stereocenter is about 7 kcal/mol for a trialkylamine.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] The interconversion has been compared to the inversion of an open umbrella into a strong wind.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Amines of the type NHRR' and NRR′R″ are chiral: the nitrogen center bears four substituents counting the lone pair.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Because of the low barrier to inversion, amines of the type NHRR' cannot be obtained in optical purity.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] For chiral tertiary amines, NRR′R″ can only be resolved when the R, R', and R″ groups are constrained in cyclic structures such as *N*-substituted aziridines (quaternary ammonium salts are resolvable).
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] In aromatic amines ("anilines"), nitrogen is often nearly planar owing to conjugation of the lone pair with the aryl substituent.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] The C-N distance is correspondingly shorter.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] In aniline, the C–N distance is the same as the C–C distances.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Compared to alkali metal hydroxides, amines are weaker.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] The degree of solvation of the protonated amine, which includes steric hindrance by the groups on nitrogen.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Owing to inductive effects, the basicity of an amine might be expected to increase with the number of alkyl groups on the amine.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Correlations are complicated owing to the effects of solvation which are opposite the trends for inductive effects.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Solvation effects also dominate the basicity of aromatic amines (anilines).
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] For anilines, the lone pair of electrons on nitrogen delocalizes into the ring, resulting in decreased basicity.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Substituents on the aromatic ring, and their positions relative to the amino group, also affect basicity as seen in the table.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Solvation significantly affects the basicity of amines.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] N−H groups strongly interact with water, especially in ammonium ions.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Consequently, the basicity of ammonia is enhanced by 1011 by solvation.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] The intrinsic basicity of amines, i.e. the situation where solvation is unimportant, has been evaluated in the gas phase.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] In the gas phase, amines exhibit the basicities predicted from the electron-releasing effects of the organic substituents.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Thus tertiary amines are more basic than secondary amines, which are more basic than primary amines, and finally ammonia is least basic.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] The order of pKb values (basicities in water) does not follow this order.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Similarly, aniline is more basic than ammonia in the gas phase, but ten thousand times less so in aqueous solution.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] In aprotic polar solvents such as DMSO, DMF, and acetonitrile the energy of solvation is not as high as in protic polar solvents like water and methanol.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] For this reason, the basicity of amines in these aprotic solvents is almost solely governed by the electronic effects.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] In such reactions, which are more useful for alkyl iodides and bromides, the degree of alkylation is difficult to control such that one obtains mixtures of primary, secondary, and tertiary amines, as well as quaternary ammonium salts.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Selectivity can be improved via the Delépine reaction, although this is rarely employed on an industrial scale.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Selectivity is also assured in the Gabriel synthesis, which involves organohalide reacting with potassium phthalimide.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Aryl halides are much less reactive toward amines and for that reason are more controllable.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] A popular way to prepare aryl amines is the Buchwald-Hartwig reaction.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Disubstituted alkenes react with HCN in the presence of strong acids to give formamides, which can be decarbonylated.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] This method, the Ritter reaction, is used industrially to produce tertiary amines such as *tert*-octylamine.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Hydroamination of alkenes is also widely practiced.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] The reaction is catalyzed by zeolite-based solid acids.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] A nickel catalyst can hydrogenate unsaturated N-containing functional groups to amines.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Suitable groups include nitriles, imines (including oximes), amides, azides, and nitro groups.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Many amines are produced from aldehydes and ketones via reductive amination, reduction of an imine formed *in situ* or a two-step process.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] LiAlH4 is more commonly employed to reduce these groups at laboratory scale.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] In the case of nitriles, reactions are sensitive to acidic or alkaline conditions, which can hydrolyze the −CN group.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Aniline (C6H5NH2) and derivatives are prepared by reduction of the corresponding nitroaromatics.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] In industry, hydrogen is the preferred reductant, whereas tin and iron are often employed in the laboratory.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Many methods exist for the preparation of amines, many of these methods being rather specialized.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Aside from their basicity, the dominant reactivity of amines is their nucleophilicity.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Most primary amines are good ligands for metal ions to give coordination complexes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Acyl chlorides and acid anhydrides react with primary and secondary amines to form amides (the "Schotten–Baumann reaction").
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Similarly, with sulfonyl chlorides, one obtains sulfonamides.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] This transformation, known as the Hinsberg reaction, is a chemical test for the presence of amines.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Because amines are basic, they neutralize acids to form the corresponding ammonium salts R3NH+.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] When formed from carboxylic acids and primary and secondary amines, these salts thermally dehydrate to form the corresponding amides.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Amines reacts with nitrous acid to give diazonium salts.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] The alkyl diazonium salts are of little importance because they are too unstable.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Anilines and naphthylamines form more stable diazonium salts, which can be isolated in the crystalline form.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Diazonium salts undergo a variety of useful transformations involving replacement of the N2 group with anions.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Aryldiazoniums couple with electron-rich aromatic compounds such as a phenol to form azo compounds.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Such reactions are widely applied to the production of dyes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Imine formation is an important reaction.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Primary amines react with ketones and aldehydes to form imines.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] The breakdown of amino acids releases amines, famously in the case of decaying fish which smell of trimethylamine.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Many neurotransmitters are amines, including epinephrine, norepinephrine, dopamine, serotonin, and histamine.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Protonated amino groups (–NH+3) are the most common positively charged moieties in proteins, specifically in the amino acid lysine.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] The anionic polymer DNA is typically bound to various amine-rich proteins.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Additionally, the terminal charged primary ammonium on lysine forms salt bridges with carboxylate groups of other amino acids in polypeptides, which is one of the primary influences on the three-dimensional structures of proteins.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Hormones derived from the modification of amino acids are referred to as amine hormones.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Typically, the original structure of the amino acid is modified such that a –COOH, or carboxyl, group is removed, whereas the –NH+3, or amine, group remains.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Amine hormones are synthesized from the amino acids tryptophan or tyrosine.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Primary aromatic amines are used as a starting material for the manufacture of azo dyes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] It reacts with nitrous acid to form diazonium salt, which can undergo coupling reaction to form an azo compound.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Aqueous monoethanolamine (MEA), diglycolamine (DGA), diethanolamine (DEA), diisopropanolamine (DIPA) and methyldiethanolamine (MDEA) are widely used industrially for removing carbon dioxide (CO2) and hydrogen sulfide (H2S) from natural gas and refinery process streams.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] They may also be used to remove CO2 from combustion gases and flue gases and may have potential for abatement of greenhouse gases.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Related processes are known as sweetening.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Amines are often used as epoxy resin curing agents.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] These include dimethylethylamine, cyclohexylamine, and a variety of diamines such as 4,4-diaminodicyclohexylmethane.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Multifunctional amines such as tetraethylenepentamine and triethylenetetramine are also widely used in this capacity.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] The reaction proceeds by the lone pair of electrons on the amine nitrogen attacking the outermost carbon on the oxirane ring of the epoxy resin.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] This relieves ring strain on the epoxide and is the driving force of the reaction.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Molecules with tertiary amine functionality are often used to accelerate the epoxy-amine curing reaction and include substances such as 2,4,6-Tris(dimethylaminomethyl)phenol.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] It has been stated that this is the most widely used room temperature accelerator for two-component epoxy resin systems.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Low molecular weight simple amines, such as ethylamine, are toxic with LD50 between 100 and 1000 mg/kg.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] They are skin irritants, especially as some are easily absorbed through the skin.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-amine] Amines are a broad class of compounds, and more complex members of the class can be extremely bioactive, for example strychnine.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-compound] In organic chemistry, hydrocarbons (compounds composed solely of carbon and hydrogen) are divided into two classes: aromatic compounds and **aliphatic compounds** (/ˌælɪˈfætɪk/; G.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-compound] Aliphatic compounds can be saturated (in which all the C-C bonds are single, requiring the structure to be completed, or 'saturated', by hydrogen) like hexane, or unsaturated, like hexene and hexyne.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-compound] Open-chain compounds, whether straight or branched, and which contain no rings of any type, are always aliphatic.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-compound] Cyclic compounds can be aliphatic if they are not aromatic.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-compound] Aliphatic compounds can be saturated, joined by single bonds (alkanes), or unsaturated, with double bonds (alkenes) or triple bonds (alkynes).
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-compound] If other elements (heteroatoms) are bound to the carbon chain, the most common being oxygen, nitrogen, sulfur, and chlorine, it is no longer a hydrocarbon, and therefore no longer an aliphatic compound.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-compound] However, such compounds may still be referred to as aliphatic if the hydrocarbon portion of the molecule is aliphatic, e.g. aliphatic amines, to differentiate them from aromatic amines.
[src:aliphatic-compound/aliphatic-compound] The least complex aliphatic compound is methane (CH4).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] In organic chemistry, an **alkane**, or **paraffin** (a historical trivial name that also has other meanings), is an acyclic saturated hydrocarbon.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] In other words, an alkane consists of hydrogen and carbon atoms arranged in a tree structure in which all the carbon–carbon bonds are single.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Alkanes have the general chemical formula C*n*H2*n*+2.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The alkanes range in complexity from the simplest case of methane (CH4), where *n* = 1 (sometimes called the parent molecule), to arbitrarily large and complex molecules, like hexacontane (C60H122) or 4-methyl-5-(1-methylethyl) octane, an isomer of dodecane (C12H26).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) defines alkanes as "acyclic branched or unbranched hydrocarbons having the general formula C*n*H2*n*+2, and therefore consisting entirely of hydrogen atoms and saturated carbon atoms".
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] However, some sources use the term to denote *any* saturated hydrocarbon, including those that are either monocyclic (i.e. the cycloalkanes) or polycyclic, despite them having a distinct general formula (e.g. cycloalkanes are C*n*H2*n*).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] In an alkane, each carbon atom is sp3-hybridized with 4 sigma bonds (either C–C or C–H), and each hydrogen atom is joined to one of the carbon atoms (in a C–H bond).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The longest series of linked carbon atoms in a molecule is known as its carbon skeleton or carbon backbone.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The number of carbon atoms may be considered as the size of the alkane.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] One group of the higher alkanes are waxes, solids at standard ambient temperature and pressure (SATP), for which the number of carbon atoms in the carbon backbone is greater than about 17.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Methane is produced by methanogenic archaea and some long-chain alkanes function as pheromones in certain animal species or as protective waxes in plants and fungi.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Nevertheless, most alkanes do not have much biological activity.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] They can be viewed as molecular trees upon which can be hung the more active/reactive functional groups of biological molecules.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The alkanes have two main commercial sources: petroleum (crude oil) and natural gas.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] An alkyl group is an alkane-based molecular fragment that bears one open valence for bonding.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] They are generally abbreviated with the symbol for any organyl group, R, although Alk is sometimes used to specifically symbolize an alkyl group (as opposed to an alkenyl group or aryl group).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Ordinarily, the C–C single bond distance is 1.53 ångströms (1.53×10−10 m).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Saturated hydrocarbons can be linear, branched, or cyclic.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The third group is sometimes called cycloalkanes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Very complicated structures are possible by combining linear, branched, cyclic alkanes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Alkanes with more than three carbon atoms can be arranged in various ways, forming structural isomers.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The simplest isomer of an alkane is the one in which the carbon atoms are arranged in a single chain with no branches.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] This isomer is sometimes called the *n*-isomer (*n* for "normal", although it is not necessarily the most common).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] However, the chain of carbon atoms may also be branched at one or more points.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The number of possible isomers increases rapidly with the number of carbon atoms.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] For example, 3-methylhexane and its higher homologues are chiral due to their stereogenic center at carbon atom number 3.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The above list only includes differences of connectivity, not stereochemistry.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] In addition to the alkane isomers, the chain of carbon atoms may form one or more rings.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Such compounds are called cycloalkanes, and are also excluded from the above list because changing the number of rings changes the molecular formula.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] For example, cyclobutane and methylcyclopropane are isomers of each other (C4H8), but are not isomers of butane (C4H10).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Branched alkanes are more thermodynamically stable than their linear (or less branched) isomers.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] For example, the highly branched 2,2,3,3-tetramethylbutane is about 1.9 kcal/mol more stable than its linear isomer, *n*-octane.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The IUPAC nomenclature (systematic way of naming compounds) for alkanes is based on identifying hydrocarbon chains.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Unbranched, saturated hydrocarbon chains are named systematically with a Greek numerical prefix denoting the number of carbons and the suffix "-ane".
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] In 1866, August Wilhelm von Hofmann suggested systematizing nomenclature by using the whole sequence of vowels a, e, i, o and u to create suffixes -ane, -ene, -ine (or -yne), -one, -une, for the hydrocarbons C*n*H2*n*+2, C*n*H2*n*, C*n*H2*n*−2, C*n*H2*n*−4, C*n*H2*n*−6.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] In modern nomenclature, the first three specifically name hydrocarbons with single, double and triple bonds; while "-one" now represents a ketone.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Straight-chain alkanes are sometimes indicated by the prefix *n*- (for "normal") where a non-linear isomer exists.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Alternative names for this group used in the petroleum industry are **linear paraffins** or ***n*-paraffins**.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The first four names were derived from methanol, ether, propionic acid and butyric acid.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Alkanes with five or more carbon atoms are named by adding the suffix **-ane** to the appropriate numerical multiplier prefix with elision of any terminal vowel (*-a* or *-o*) from the basic numerical term.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The numeral prefix is generally Greek; however, alkanes with a carbon atom count ending in nine, for example nonane, use the Latin prefix **non-**.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Simple branched alkanes often have a common name using a prefix to distinguish them from linear alkanes, for example *n*-butane, isobutane (or *i*-butane) for the two isomers of butane and *n*-pentane, isopentane, neopentane for the three isomers of pentane.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] IUPAC naming conventions can be used to produce a systematic name.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Though technically distinct from the alkanes, this class of hydrocarbons is referred to by some as the "cyclic alkanes." As their description implies, they contain one or more rings.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Simple cycloalkanes have a prefix "cyclo-" to distinguish them from alkanes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Cycloalkanes are named as per their acyclic counterparts with respect to the number of carbon atoms in their backbones, e.g., cyclopentane (C5H10) is a cycloalkane with 5 carbon atoms just like pentane (C5H12), but they are joined up in a five-membered ring.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] In a similar manner, propane and cyclopropane, butane and cyclobutane, etc.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Substituted cycloalkanes are named similarly to substituted alkanes – the cycloalkane ring is stated, and the substituents are according to their position on the ring, with the numbering decided by the Cahn–Ingold–Prelog priority rules.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The trivial (non-systematic) name for alkanes is "paraffins".
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Together, alkanes are known as the "paraffin series".
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Trivial names for compounds are usually historical artifacts.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] They were coined before the development of systematic names, and have been retained due to familiar usage in industry.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Cycloalkanes are also called naphthenes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Branched-chain alkanes are called **isoparaffins**.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] "Paraffin" is a general term and often does not distinguish between pure compounds and mixtures of isomers, i.e., compounds of the same chemical formula, e.g., pentane and isopentane.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Alkanes with the lowest molecular weights are gases, those of intermediate molecular weight are liquids, and the heaviest are waxy solids.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Alkanes experiences intermolecular van der Waals forces.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The cumulative effects of these intermolecular forces give rise to greater boiling points of alkanes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Under standard conditions, from CH4 to C4H10 alkanes are gaseous; from C5H12 to C17H36 they are liquids; and after C18H38 they are solids.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] As the boiling point of alkanes is primarily determined by weight, it should not be a surprise that the boiling point has an almost linear relationship with the size (molecular weight) of the molecule.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] As a rule of thumb, the boiling point rises 20–30 °C for each carbon added to the chain; this rule applies to other homologous series.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] A straight-chain alkane will have a boiling point higher than a branched-chain alkane due to the greater surface area in contact, and thus greater van der Waals forces, between adjacent molecules.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] For example, compare isobutane (2-methylpropane) and *n*-butane, which boil at −12 and 0 °C, and 2,2-dimethylbutane and 2,3-dimethylbutane which boil at 50 and 58 °C, respectively.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] On the other hand, cycloalkanes tend to have higher boiling points than their linear counterparts due to the locked conformations of the molecules, which give a plane of intermolecular contact.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The melting points of the alkanes follow a similar trend to boiling points for the same reason as outlined above.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] That is, (all other things being equal) the larger the molecule the higher the melting point.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] However, alkanes' melting points follow a more complex pattern, due to variations in the properties of their solid crystals.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] One difference in crystal structure that even-numbered alkanes (from hexane onwards) tend to form denser-packed crystals compared to their odd-numbered neighbors.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] This causes them to have a greater enthalpy of fusion (amount of energy required to melt them), raising their melting point.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] A second difference in crystal structure is that even-numbered alkanes (from octane onwards) tend to form more rotationally ordered crystals compared to their odd-numbered neighbors.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] This causes them to have a greater entropy of fusion (increase in disorder from the solid to the liquid state), lowering their melting point.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] While these effects operate in opposing directions, the first effect tends to be slightly stronger, leading even-numbered alkanes to have slightly higher melting points than the average of their odd-numbered neighbors.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] This trend does not apply to methane, which has an unusually high melting point, higher than both ethane and propane.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] This is because it has a very low entropy of fusion, attributable to its high molecular symmetry and the rotational disorder in solid methane near its melting point (Methane I).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The melting points of branched-chain alkanes can be either higher or lower than those of the corresponding straight-chain alkanes, again depending on these two factors.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] More symmetric alkanes tend towards higher melting points, due to enthalpic effects when they form ordered crystals, and entropic effects when they form disordered crystals (e.g. neopentane).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Alkanes do not conduct electricity in any way, nor are they substantially polarized by an electric field.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] For this reason, they do not form hydrogen bonds and are insoluble in polar solvents such as water.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Since the hydrogen bonds between individual water molecules are aligned away from an alkane molecule, the coexistence of an alkane and water leads to an increase in molecular order (a reduction in entropy).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] As there is no significant bonding between water molecules and alkane molecules, the second law of thermodynamics suggests that this reduction in entropy should be minimized by minimizing the contact between alkane and water: Alkanes are said to be hydrophobic as they are insoluble in water.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Their solubility in nonpolar solvents is relatively high, a property that is called lipophilicity.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Alkanes are, for example, miscible in all proportions among themselves.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The density of the alkanes usually increases with the number of carbon atoms but remains less than that of water.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Hence, alkanes form the upper layer in an alkane–water mixture.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The molecular structure of the alkanes directly affects their physical and chemical characteristics.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] It is derived from the electron configuration of carbon, which has four valence electrons.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The carbon atoms in alkanes are described as sp3 hybrids; that is to say that, to a good approximation, the valence electrons are in orbitals directed towards the corners of a tetrahedron which are derived from the combination of the 2s orbital and the three 2p orbitals.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] This is exact for the case of methane, while larger alkanes containing a combination of C–H and C–C bonds generally have bonds that are within several degrees of this idealized value.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] An alkane has only C–H and C–C single bonds.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The former result from the overlap of an sp3 orbital of carbon with the 1s orbital of a hydrogen; the latter by the overlap of two sp3 orbitals on adjacent carbon atoms.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The bond lengths amount to 1.09 × 10−10 m for a C–H bond and 1.54 × 10−10 m for a C–C bond.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The spatial arrangement of the bonds is similar to that of the four sp3 orbitals—they are tetrahedrally arranged, with an angle of 109.47° between them.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Structural formulae that represent the bonds as being at right angles to one another, while both common and useful, do not accurately depict the geometry.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The spatial arrangement of the C-C and C-H bonds are described by the torsion angles of the molecule, known as its conformation.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] In ethane, the simplest case for studying the conformation of alkanes, there is nearly free rotation about a carbon–carbon single bond.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Two limiting conformations are important: eclipsed conformation and staggered conformation.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The staggered conformation is 12.6 kJ/mol (3.0 kcal/mol) lower in energy (more stable) than the eclipsed conformation (the least stable).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] In highly branched alkanes, the bond angle may differ from the optimal value (109.5°) to accommodate bulky groups.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Such distortions introduce a tension in the molecule, known as steric hindrance or strain.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Strain substantially increases reactivity.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Spectroscopic signatures for alkanes are obtainable by the major characterization techniques.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The C-H stretching mode gives strong absorptions between 2850 and 2960 cm−1 and weaker bands for the C-C stretching mode absorbs between 800 and 1300 cm−1.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The carbon–hydrogen bending modes depend on the nature of the group: methyl groups show bands at 1450 cm−1 and 1375 cm−1, while methylene groups show bands at 1465 cm−1 and 1450 cm−1.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Carbon chains with more than four carbon atoms show a weak absorption at around 725 cm−1.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The proton resonances of alkanes are usually found at *δ*H = 0.5–1.5.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The carbon-13 resonances depend on the number of hydrogen atoms attached to the carbon: *δ*C = 8–30 (primary, methyl, –CH3), 15–55 (secondary, methylene, –CH2–), 20–60 (tertiary, methyne, C–H) and quaternary.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The carbon-13 resonance of quaternary carbon atoms is characteristically weak, due to the lack of nuclear Overhauser effect and the long relaxation time, and can be missed in weak samples, or samples that have not been run for a sufficiently long time.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Since alkanes have high ionization energies, their electron impact mass spectra show weak currents for their molecular ions.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The fragmentation pattern can be difficult to interpret, but in the case of branched chain alkanes, the carbon chain is preferentially cleaved at tertiary or quaternary carbons due to the relative stability of the resulting free radicals.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The mass spectra for straight-chain alkanes is illustrated by that for dodecane: the fragment resulting from the loss of a single methyl group (*M* − 15) is absent, fragments are more intense than the molecular ion and are spaced by intervals of 14 mass units, corresponding to loss of CH2 groups.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Alkanes are only weakly reactive with most chemical compounds.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] They only react with the strongest of electrophilic reagents by virtue of their strong C–H bonds (~100 kcal/mol) and C–C bonds (~90 kcal/mol).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] They are also relatively unreactive toward free radicals.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] This inertness is the source of the term *paraffins* (with the meaning here of "lacking affinity").
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] In crude oil the alkane molecules have remained chemically unchanged for millions of years.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The acid dissociation constant (p*K*a) values of all alkanes are estimated to range from 50 to 70, depending on the extrapolation method, hence they are extremely weak acids that are practically inert to bases (see: carbon acids).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] They are also extremely weak bases, undergoing no observable protonation in pure sulfuric acid (*H*0 ~ −12), although superacids that are at least millions of times stronger have been known to protonate them to give hypercoordinate alkanium ions (see: methanium ion).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Thus, a mixture of antimony pentafluoride (SbF5) and fluorosulfonic acid (HSO3F), called magic acid, can protonate alkanes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] All alkanes react with oxygen in a combustion reaction, although they become increasingly difficult to ignite as the number of carbon atoms increases.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] See the alkane heat of formation table for detailed data.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The standard enthalpy change of combustion, Δc*H*⊖, for alkanes increases by about 650 kJ/mol per CH2 group.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Branched-chain alkanes have lower values of Δc*H*⊖ than straight-chain alkanes of the same number of carbon atoms, and so can be seen to be somewhat more stable.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Some organisms are capable of metabolizing alkanes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The methane monooxygenases convert methane to methanol.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] For higher alkanes, cytochrome P450 convert alkanes to alcohols, which are then susceptible to degradation.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Free radicals, molecules with unpaired electrons, play a large role in most reactions of alkanes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Free radical halogenation reactions occur with halogens, leading to the production of haloalkanes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The hydrogen atoms of the alkane are progressively replaced by halogen atoms.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The reaction of alkanes and fluorine is highly exothermic and can lead to an explosion.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] These reactions are an important industrial route to halogenated hydrocarbons.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Experiments have shown that all halogenation produces a mixture of all possible isomers, indicating that all hydrogen atoms are susceptible to reaction.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The mixture produced, however, is not statistical: Secondary and tertiary hydrogen atoms are preferentially replaced due to the greater stability of secondary and tertiary free-radicals.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] In the Reed reaction, sulfur dioxide and chlorine convert hydrocarbons to sulfonyl chlorides under the influence of light.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Under some conditions, alkanes will undergo nitration.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Certain transition metal complexes promote non-radical reactions with alkanes, resulting in C–H bond activation reactions.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Cracking breaks larger molecules into smaller ones.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] This reaction requires heat and catalysts.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The thermal cracking process follows a homolytic mechanism with formation of free radicals.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The catalytic cracking process involves the presence of acid catalysts (usually solid acids such as silica-alumina and zeolites), which promote a heterolytic (asymmetric) breakage of bonds yielding pairs of ions of opposite charges, usually a carbocation.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Carbon-localized free radicals and cations are both highly unstable and undergo processes of chain rearrangement, C–C scission in position beta (i.e., cracking) and intra- and intermolecular hydrogen transfer or hydride transfer.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] In both types of processes, the corresponding reactive intermediates (radicals, ions) are permanently regenerated, and thus they proceed by a self-propagating chain mechanism.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The chain of reactions is eventually terminated by radical or ion recombination.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Dragan and his colleague were the first to report about isomerization in alkanes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Isomerization and reformation are processes in which straight-chain alkanes are heated in the presence of a platinum catalyst.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] In isomerization, the alkanes become branched-chain isomers.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] In other words, it does not lose any carbons or hydrogens, keeping the same molecular weight.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] In reformation, the alkanes become cycloalkanes or aromatic hydrocarbons, giving off hydrogen as a by-product.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Both of these processes raise the octane number of the substance.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Butane is the most common alkane that is put under the process of isomerization, as it makes many branched alkanes with high octane numbers.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] In steam reforming, alkanes react with steam in the presence of a nickel catalyst to give hydrogen and carbon monoxide.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Alkanes form a small portion of the atmospheres of the outer gas planets such as Jupiter (0.1% methane, 2 ppm ethane), Saturn (0.2% methane, 5 ppm ethane), Uranus (1.99% methane, 2.5 ppm ethane) and Neptune (1.5% methane, 1.5 ppm ethane).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Titan (1.6% methane), a satellite of Saturn, was examined by the *Huygens* probe, which indicated that Titan's atmosphere periodically rains liquid methane onto the moon's surface.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Also on Titan, the Cassini mission has imaged seasonal methane/ethane lakes near the polar regions of Titan.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Methane and ethane have been detected in the tail of the comet Hyakutake.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Chemical analysis showed that the abundances of ethane and methane were roughly equal, which is thought to imply that its ices formed in interstellar space, away from the Sun, which would have evaporated these volatile molecules.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Alkanes have been detected in meteorites such as carbonaceous chondrites.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Traces of methane gas (about 0.0002% or 1745 ppb) occur in the Earth's atmosphere, produced primarily by methanogenic microorganisms, such as Archaea in the gut of ruminants.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The most important commercial sources for alkanes are natural gas and oil.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Natural gas contains primarily methane and ethane, with some propane and butane: oil is a mixture of liquid alkanes and other hydrocarbons.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] These hydrocarbons were formed when marine animals and plants (zooplankton and phytoplankton) died and sank to the bottom of ancient seas and were covered with sediments in an anoxic environment and converted over many millions of years at high temperatures and high pressure to their current form.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] These hydrocarbon deposits, collected in porous rocks trapped beneath impermeable cap rocks, comprise commercial oil fields.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] They have formed over millions of years and once exhausted cannot be readily replaced.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The depletion of these hydrocarbons reserves is the basis for what is known as the energy crisis.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Alkanes have a low solubility in water, so the content in the oceans is negligible; however, at high pressures and low temperatures (such as at the bottom of the oceans), methane can co-crystallize with water to form a solid methane clathrate (methane hydrate).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Although this cannot be commercially exploited at the present time, the amount of combustible energy of the known methane clathrate fields exceeds the energy content of all the natural gas and oil deposits put together.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Methane extracted from methane clathrate is, therefore, a candidate for future fuels.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Aside from petroleum and natural gas, alkanes occur significantly in nature only as methane, which is produced by some archaea by the process of methanogenesis.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] These organisms are found in the gut of termites and cows.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The methane is produced from carbon dioxide or other organic compounds.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] It is probable that our current deposits of natural gas were formed in a similar way.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Certain types of bacteria can metabolize alkanes: they prefer even-numbered carbon chains as they are easier to degrade than odd-numbered chains.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Alkanes play a negligible role in higher organisms, with rare exception.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Some yeasts, e.g., *Candida tropicale*, *Pichia* sp., *Rhodotorula* sp., can use alkanes as a source of carbon or energy.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The fungus *Amorphotheca resinae* prefers the longer-chain alkanes in aviation fuel, and can cause serious problems for aircraft in tropical regions.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] In plants, the solid long-chain alkanes are found in the plant cuticle and epicuticular wax of many species, but are only rarely major constituents.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] They protect the plant against water loss, prevent the leaching of important minerals by the rain, and protect against bacteria, fungi, and harmful insects.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The carbon chains in plant alkanes are usually odd-numbered, between 27 and 33 carbon atoms in length, and are made by the plants by decarboxylation of even-numbered fatty acids.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The exact composition of the layer of wax is not only species-dependent but also changes with the season and such environmental factors as lighting conditions, temperature or humidity.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The Jeffrey pine is noted for producing exceptionally high levels of *n*-heptane in its resin, for which reason its distillate was designated as the zero point for one octane rating.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Floral scents have also long been known to contain volatile alkane components, and *n*-nonane is a significant component in the scent of some roses.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Emission of gaseous and volatile alkanes such as ethane, pentane, and hexane by plants has also been documented at low levels, though they are not generally considered to be a major component of biogenic air pollution.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Alkanes are important as pheromones, chemical messenger materials, on which insects depend for communication.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] 7-methyltricosane and 9-methyltricosane are active for ladybird beetles (*Adalia bipunctata*).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The emerald ash borer (*Agrilus planipennis Fairmaire*) responds to 9-methylpentacosane.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Female Asian long-horned beetles *Anoplophora glabripennis*, which are very damaging, secrete 2-methyldocosane.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Waggle-dancing honey bees produce and release two alkanes, tricosane and pentacosane.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] One example, in which both plant and animal alkanes play a role, is the ecological relationship between the sand bee (*Andrena nigroaenea*) and the early spider orchid (*Ophrys sphegodes*); the latter is dependent for pollination on the former.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Sand bees use pheromones in order to identify a mate; in the case of *A. nigroaenea*, the females emit a mixture of tricosane (C23H48), pentacosane (C25H52) and heptacosane (C27H56) in the ratio 3:3:1, and males are attracted by specifically this odor.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The orchid takes advantage of this mating arrangement to get the male bee to collect and disseminate its pollen; parts of its flower not only resemble the appearance of sand bees but also produce large quantities of the three alkanes in the same ratio as female sand bees.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] As a result, numerous males are lured to the blooms and attempt to copulate with their imaginary partner: although this endeavor is not crowned with success for the bee, it allows the orchid to transfer its pollen, which will be dispersed after the departure of the frustrated male to other blooms.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The most important source of alkanes is natural gas and crude oil.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Alkanes are separated in an oil refinery by fractional distillation.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Another route to alkanes is hydrogenolysis, which entails cleavage of C-heteroatom bonds using hydrogen.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] In industry, the main substrates are organonitrogen and organosulfur impurities, i.e. the heteroatoms are N and S.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Hydrogenolysis can be applied to the conversion of virtually any functional group into hydrocarbons.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Substrates include haloalkanes, alcohols, aldehydes, ketones, carboxylic acids, etc.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Both hydrogenolysis and hydrogenation are practiced in refineries.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] They can be effected by using lithium aluminium hydride, Clemmenson reduction and other specialized routes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Coal is a more traditional precursor to alkanes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] A wide range of technologies have been intensively practiced for centuries.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Simply heating coal gives alkanes, leaving behind coke.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Relevant technologies include the Bergius process and coal liquefaction.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Partial combustion of coal and related solid organic compounds generates carbon monoxide, which can be hydrogenated using the Fischer–Tropsch process.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] This technology allows the synthesis of liquid hydrocarbons, including alkanes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] This method is used to produce substitutes for petroleum distillates.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Rarely is there any interest in the synthesis of alkanes, since they are usually commercially available and less valued than virtually any precursor.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The best-known method is hydrogenation of alkenes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Many C−X bonds can be converted to C−H bonds using lithium aluminium hydride, Clemmenson reduction, and other specialized routes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Hydrolysis of alkyl Grignard reagents and alkyl organolithium reagents gives alkanes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] The dominant use of alkanes is as fuels.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Propane and butane, easily liquified gases, are commonly known as liquified petroleum gas (LPG).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] From pentane to octane the alkanes are highly volatile liquids.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] They are used as fuels in internal combustion engines, as they vaporize easily on entry into the combustion chamber without forming droplets, which would impair the uniformity of the combustion.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Branched-chain alkanes are preferred as they are much less prone to premature ignition, which causes knocking, than their straight-chain homologues.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] This propensity to premature ignition is measured by the octane rating of the fuel, where 2,2,4-trimethylpentane (*isooctane*) has an arbitrary value of 100, and heptane has a value of zero.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Apart from their use as fuels, the middle alkanes are also good solvents for nonpolar substances.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Alkanes from nonane to, for instance, hexadecane (an alkane with sixteen carbon atoms) are liquids of higher viscosity, less and less suitable for use in gasoline.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] They form instead the major part of diesel and aviation fuel.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Diesel fuels are characterized by their cetane number, cetane being an old name for hexadecane.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] However, the higher melting points of these alkanes can cause problems at low temperatures and in polar regions, where the fuel becomes too thick to flow correctly.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] By the process of cracking, alkanes can be converted to alkenes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Simple alkenes are precursors to polymers, such as polyethylene and polypropylene.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] When the cracking is taken to extremes, alkanes can be converted to carbon black, which is a significant tire component.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Chlorination of methane gives chloromethanes, which are used as solvents and building blocks for complex compounds.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Similarly treatment of methane with sulfur gives carbon disulfide.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Still other chemicals are prepared by reaction with sulfur trioxide and nitric oxide.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Some light hydrocarbons are used as aerosol sprays.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Alkanes from hexadecane upwards form the most important components of fuel oil and lubricating oil.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] In the latter function, they work at the same time as anti-corrosive agents, as their hydrophobic nature means that water cannot reach the metal surface.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Many solid alkanes find use as paraffin wax, for example, in candles.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] This should not be confused however with true wax, which consists primarily of esters.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Alkanes with a chain length of approximately 35 or more carbon atoms are found in bitumen, used, for example, in road surfacing.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] However, the higher alkanes have little value and are usually split into lower alkanes by cracking.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Alkanes are highly flammable, but they have low toxicities.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Methane "is toxicologically virtually inert".
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkane] Alkanes can be asphyxiants and narcotic.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] In organic chemistry, an **alkene**, or **olefin**, is a hydrocarbon containing one or more carbon–carbon double bonds.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The double bond may be internal or at the terminal position.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Terminal alkenes are also known as **α-olefins**.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Acyclic alkenes, with only one double bond and no other functional groups (also known as **mono-enes**) form a homologous series of hydrocarbons with the general formula C*n*H2*n* with *n* being a >1 natural number (which is two hydrogens less than the corresponding alkane).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] When *n* is four or more, isomers are possible, distinguished by the position and conformation of the double bond.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Alkenes are generally colorless non-polar compounds, somewhat similar to alkanes but more reactive.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The first few members of the series are gases or liquids at room temperature.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The simplest alkene, ethylene (C2H4) (or "ethene" in the IUPAC nomenclature) is the organic compound produced on the largest scale industrially.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Aromatic compounds are often drawn as cyclic alkenes, however their structure and properties are sufficiently distinct that they are not classified as alkenes or olefins.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Hydrocarbons with two overlapping double bonds (C=C=C) are called allenes—the simplest such compound is itself called *allene*—and those with three or more overlapping bonds (C=C=C=C, C=C=C=C=C, etc.) are called cumulenes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] A carbon–carbon double bond consists of a sigma bond and a pi bond.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] This double bond is stronger than a single covalent bond: 611 kJ/mol vs.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Double bonds are shorter than single bonds with an average bond length of 1.33 Å (133 pm) vs 1.53 Å for a typical C-C single bond.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] In one bonding model, the carbon atom of the double bond is sp2 hybridized.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The sp2 orbitals form sigma bonds to three atoms (the other carbon atom and two hydrogen atoms).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The unhybridized 2p atomic orbital, which lie perpendicular to the plane of the three sp2 orbitals, combine to form the pi bond.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] This bond lies outside the main C–C axis, with half of the bond on one side of the molecule and a half on the other.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] With a strength of 65 kcal/mol, the pi bond is significantly weaker than the sigma bond.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Rotation about the carbon–carbon double bond is restricted because it incurs an energetic cost to break the alignment of the p orbitals on the two carbon atoms.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Consequently *cis* or *trans* isomers interconvert so slowly that they can be freely handled at ambient conditions without isomerization.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] More complex alkenes may be named with the *E*–*Z* notation for molecules with three or four different substituents (side groups).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] For example, of the isomers of butene, the two methyl groups of (*Z*)-but-2-ene (a.k.a.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] *cis*-2-butene) appear on the same side of the double bond, and in (*E*)-but-2-ene (a.k.a.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] *trans*-2-butene) the methyl groups appear on opposite sides.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] These two isomers of butene have distinct properties.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] As predicted by the VSEPR model of electron pair repulsion, the molecular geometry of alkenes includes bond angles about each carbon atom in a double bond of about 120°.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The angle may vary because of steric strain introduced by nonbonded interactions between functional groups attached to the carbon atoms of the double bond.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] For example, the C–C–C bond angle in propylene is 123.9°.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] For bridged alkenes, Bredt's rule states that a double bond cannot occur at the bridgehead of a bridged ring system unless the rings are large enough.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Following Fawcett and defining *S* as the total number of non-bridgehead atoms in the rings, bicyclic systems require *S* ≥ 7 for stability and tricyclic systems require *S* ≥ 11.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] In organic chemistry, the prefixes cis- and trans- are used to describe the positions of functional groups attached to carbon atoms joined by a double bond.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] In Latin, *cis* and *trans* mean "on this side of" and "on the other side of" respectively.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Therefore, if the functional groups are both on the same side of the carbon chain, the bond is said to have **cis-** configuration, otherwise (i.e. the functional groups are on the opposite side of the carbon chain), the bond is said to have **trans-** configuration.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] For there to be cis- and trans- configurations, there must be a carbon chain, or at least one functional group attached to each carbon that is the same for both.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] E- and Z- configuration can be used instead in a more general case where all four functional groups attached to carbon atoms in a double bond are different.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] E- and Z- are abbreviations of German words *zusammen* (together) and *entgegen* (opposite).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] In E- and Z-isomerism, each functional group is assigned a priority based on the Cahn–Ingold–Prelog priority rules.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] If the two groups with higher priority are on the same side of the double bond, the bond is assigned **Z-** configuration, otherwise (i.e. the two groups with higher priority are on the opposite side of the double bond), the bond is assigned **E-** configuration.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Cis- and trans- configurations do not have a fixed relationship between **E**- and **Z**-configurations.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Alkenes having four or more carbon atoms can exist as structural isomers.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Most alkenes are also isomers of cycloalkanes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Many of these molecules exhibit *cis*–*trans* isomerism.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] There may also be chiral carbon atoms particularly within the larger molecules (from C5).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The number of potential isomers increases rapidly with additional carbon atoms.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Although the nomenclature is not followed widely, according to IUPAC, an alkene is an acyclic hydrocarbon with just one double bond between carbon atoms.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Olefins comprise a larger collection of cyclic and acyclic alkenes as well as dienes and polyenes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] To form the root of the IUPAC names for straight-chain alkenes, change the *-an-* infix of the parent to *-en-*.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] For example, **CH3-CH3** is the alkane *ethANe*.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The name of **CH2=CH2** is therefore *ethENe*.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] For straight-chain alkenes with 4 or more carbon atoms, that name does not completely identify the compound.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Number the carbons in that chain starting from the end that is closest to the double bond.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Define the location *k* of the double bond as being the number of its first carbon.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Name the side groups (other than hydrogen) according to the appropriate rules.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Define the position of each side group as the number of the chain carbon it is attached to.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Write the position and name of each side group.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Write the names of the alkane with the same chain, replacing the "-ane" suffix by "*k*-ene".
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The position of the double bond is often inserted before the name of the chain (e.g.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] "2-pentene"), rather than before the suffix ("pent-2-ene").
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The positions need not be indicated if they are unique.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Note that the double bond may imply a different chain numbering than that used for the corresponding alkane: (H 3C) 3C–CH 2–CH 3 is "2,2-dimethyl pentane", whereas (H 3C) 3C–CH=CH 2 is "3,3-dimethyl 1-pentene".
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] More complex rules apply for polyenes and cycloalkenes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] If the double bond of an acyclic mono-ene is not the first bond of the chain, the name as constructed above still does not completely identify the compound, because of *cis*–*trans* isomerism.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Then one must specify whether the two single C–C bonds adjacent to the double bond are on the same side of its plane, or on opposite sides.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] For monoalkenes, the configuration is often indicated by the prefixes *cis*- (from Latin "on this side of") or *trans*- ("across", "on the other side of") before the name, respectively; as in *cis*-2-pentene or *trans*-2-butene.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] More generally, *cis*–*trans* isomerism will exist if each of the two carbons of in the double bond has two different atoms or groups attached to it.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Accounting for these cases, the IUPAC recommends the more general E–Z notation, instead of the *cis* and *trans* prefixes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] This notation considers the group with highest CIP priority in each of the two carbons.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] If these two groups are on opposite sides of the double bond's plane, the configuration is labeled *E* (from the German *entgegen* meaning "opposite"); if they are on the same side, it is labeled *Z* (from German *zusammen*, "together").
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] This labeling may be taught with mnemonic "*Z* means 'on ze zame zide'".
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] IUPAC recognizes two names for hydrocarbon groups containing carbon–carbon double bonds, the vinyl group and the allyl group.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Many of the physical properties of alkenes and alkanes are similar: they are colorless, nonpolar, and combustible.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The physical state depends on molecular mass: like the corresponding saturated hydrocarbons, the simplest alkenes (ethylene, propylene, and butene) are gases at room temperature.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Linear alkenes of approximately five to nineteen carbon atoms are liquids, and higher alkenes are waxy solids.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The melting point of the solids also increases with increase in molecular mass.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Alkenes generally have stronger smells than their corresponding alkanes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Strained alkenes, in particular, like norbornene and *trans*-cyclooctene are known to have strong, unpleasant odors, a fact consistent with the stronger π complexes they form with metal ions including copper.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Below is a list of the boiling and melting points of various alkenes with the corresponding alkane and alkyne analogues.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] In the IR spectrum, the stretching/compression of C=C bond gives a peak at 1670–1600 cm−1.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The band is weak in symmetrical alkenes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] In 1H NMR spectroscopy, the hydrogen bonded to the carbon adjacent to double bonds has a δH of 4.5–6.5 ppm.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The double bond will also deshield the hydrogen attached to the carbons adjacent to sp2 carbons, and this generates δH=1.6–2 ppm peaks.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Cis/trans isomers are distinguishable due to different J-coupling effect.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Cis vicinal hydrogens will have coupling constants in the range of 6–14 Hz, whereas the trans will have coupling constants of 11–18 Hz.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] In their 13C NMR spectra, double bonds also deshield the carbons, making them have low field shift.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] C=C double bonds usually have chemical shift of about 100–170 ppm.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Like most other hydrocarbons, alkenes combust to give carbon dioxide and water.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The combustion of alkenes release less energy than burning same molarity of saturated ones with same number of carbons.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] This trend can be clearly seen in the list of standard enthalpy of combustion of hydrocarbons.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Alkenes are relatively stable compounds, but are more reactive than alkanes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Most reactions of alkenes involve additions to this pi bond, forming new single bonds.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Alkenes serve as a feedstock for the petrochemical industry because they can participate in a wide variety of reactions, prominently polymerization and alkylation.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Except for ethylene, alkenes have two sites of reactivity: the carbon–carbon pi-bond and the presence of allylic CH centers.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The former dominates but the allylic sites are important too.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Hydrogenation involves the addition of H2 "across" the double bond.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Hydrogenation reactions usually require transition metal catalysts such as palladium on carbon or PtO2.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The total number of hydrogens that can be added to an unsaturated hydrocarbon depends on its degree of unsaturation.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Comparable to hydrogenation is halogenation, the addition of a halogen molecule, such as Br2, resulting in a dihaloalkane.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Unlike hydrogenation, halogenation reactions do not require catalysts.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The reaction occurs in two steps, with a halonium ion as an intermediate.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Bromine test is used to test the saturation of hydrocarbons.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The bromine test can also be used as an indication of the degree of unsaturation for unsaturated hydrocarbons.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Bromine number is defined as gram of bromine able to react with 100g of product.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The π bonds of alkenes hydrocarbons are also susceptible to hydration.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The reaction usually requires strong acid as catalyst.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The first step in hydration often involves formation of a carbocation.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The net result of the reaction will be an alcohol.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Hydrohalogenation involves addition of H−X to unsaturated hydrocarbons.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] This reaction results in new C−H and C−X σ bonds.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The formation of the intermediate carbocation is selective and follows Markovnikov's rule.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The hydrohalogenation of alkene will result in haloalkane.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Alkenes add to dienes to give cyclohexenes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] This conversion is an example of a Diels-Alder reaction.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Such reaction proceed with retention of stereochemistry.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The rates are sensitive to electron-withdrawing or electron-donating substituents.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] When irradiated by UV-light, alkenes dimerize to give cyclobutanes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Alkenes react with ozone, leading to the scission of the double bond.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] When treated with a hot concentrated, acidified solution of KMnO4, alkenes are cleaved to form ketones and/or carboxylic acids.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The stoichiometry of the reaction is sensitive to conditions.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] This reaction and the ozonolysis can be used to determine the position of a double bond in an unknown alkene.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] This reaction is called dihydroxylation.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] In the presence of an appropriate photosensitiser, such as methylene blue and light, alkenes can undergo reaction with reactive oxygen species generated by the photosensitiser, such as hydroxyl radicals, singlet oxygen or superoxide ion.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Reactions of the excited sensitizer can involve electron or hydrogen transfer, usually with a reducing substrate (Type I reaction) or interaction with oxygen (Type II reaction).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] These various alternative processes and reactions can be controlled by choice of specific reaction conditions, leading to a wide range of products.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Terminal alkenes are precursors to polymers via processes termed polymerization.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Some polymerizations are of great economic significance, as they generate the plastics polyethylene and polypropylene.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Polymers from alkene are usually referred to as *polyolefins* although they contain no olefins.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Polymerization can proceed via diverse mechanisms.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Conjugated dienes such as buta-1,3-diene and isoprene (2-methylbuta-1,3-diene) also produce polymers, one example being natural rubber.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The presence of a C=C π bond in unsaturated hydrocarbons weakens the dissociation energy of the allylic C−H bonds.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Thus, these groupings are susceptible to free radical substitution at these C-H sites as well as addition reactions at the C=C site.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] In the presence of radical initiators, allylic C-H bonds can be halogenated.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The presence of two C=C bonds flanking one methylene, i.e., doubly allylic, results in particularly weak HC-H bonds.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The high reactivity of these situations is the basis for certain free radical reactions, manifested in the chemistry of drying oils.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Alkenes undergo olefin metathesis, which cleaves and interchanges the substituents of the alkene.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] In transition metal alkene complexes, alkenes serve as ligands for metals.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] In this case, the π electron density is donated to the metal d orbitals.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The stronger the donation is, the stronger the back bonding from the metal d orbital to π* anti-bonding orbital of the alkene.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] This effect lowers the bond order of the alkene and increases the C-C bond length.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] One example is the complex PtCl3(C2H4)]−.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] These complexes are related to the mechanisms of metal-catalyzed reactions of unsaturated hydrocarbons.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Alkenes are produced by hydrocarbon cracking.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Raw materials are mostly natural-gas condensate components (principally ethane and propane) in the US and Mideast and naphtha in Europe and Asia.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Alkanes are broken apart at high temperatures, often in the presence of a zeolite catalyst, to produce a mixture of primarily aliphatic alkenes and lower molecular weight alkanes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The mixture is feedstock and temperature dependent, and separated by fractional distillation.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] This is mainly used for the manufacture of small alkenes (up to six carbons).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Related to this is catalytic dehydrogenation, where an alkane loses hydrogen at high temperatures to produce a corresponding alkene.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] This is the reverse of the catalytic hydrogenation of alkenes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] This process is also known as reforming.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Both processes are endothermic and are driven towards the alkene at high temperatures by entropy.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Catalytic synthesis of higher α-alkenes (of the type RCH=CH2) can also be achieved by a reaction of ethylene with the organometallic compound triethylaluminium in the presence of nickel, cobalt, or platinum.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] One of the principal methods for alkene synthesis in the laboratory is the elimination reaction of alkyl halides, alcohols, and similar compounds.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Most common is the β-elimination via the E2 or E1 mechanism.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] A commercially significant example is the production of vinyl chloride.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The E2 mechanism provides a more reliable β-elimination method than E1 for most alkene syntheses.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Most E2 eliminations start with an alkyl halide or alkyl sulfonate ester (such as a tosylate or triflate).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] When an alkyl halide is used, the reaction is called a dehydrohalogenation.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] For unsymmetrical products, the more substituted alkenes (those with fewer hydrogens attached to the C=C) tend to predominate (see Zaitsev's rule).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Two common methods of elimination reactions are dehydrohalogenation of alkyl halides and dehydration of alcohols.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] A typical example is shown below; note that if possible, the H is *anti* to the leaving group, even though this leads to the less stable *Z*-isomer.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Alkenes can be synthesized from alcohols via dehydration, in which case water is lost via the E1 mechanism.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] An alcohol may also be converted to a better leaving group (e.g., xanthate), so as to allow a milder *syn*-elimination such as the Chugaev elimination and the Grieco elimination.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Related reactions include eliminations by β-haloethers (the Boord olefin synthesis; also a selenium-based elimination discussed below) and esters (ester pyrolysis).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] A thioketone and a phosphite ester combined (the Corey-Winter olefination) or diphosphorus tetraiodide will deoxygenate glycols to alkenes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Alkenes can be prepared indirectly from alkyl amines.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The amine or ammonia is not a suitable leaving group, so the amine is first either alkylated (as in the Hofmann elimination) or oxidized to an amine oxide (the Cope reaction) to render a smooth elimination possible.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The Hofmann elimination is unusual in that the *less* substituted (non-Zaitsev) alkene is usually the major product.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Alkenes are generated from α-halosulfones in the Ramberg–Bäcklund reaction, via a three-membered ring sulfone intermediate.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Another important class of methods for alkene synthesis involves construction of a new carbon–carbon double bond by coupling or condensation of a carbonyl compound (such as an aldehyde or ketone) to a carbanion or its equivalent.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Knoevenagel condensations are a related class of reactions that convert carbonyls into alkenes.Well-known methods are called *olefinations*.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The Wittig reaction is illustrative, but other related methods are known, including the Horner–Wadsworth–Emmons reaction.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The Wittig reaction involves reaction of an aldehyde or ketone with a Wittig reagent (or phosphorane) of the type Ph3P=CHR to produce an alkene and Ph3P=O.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The Wittig reagent is itself prepared easily from triphenylphosphine and an alkyl halide.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Related to the Wittig reaction is the Peterson olefination, which uses silicon-based reagents in place of the phosphorane.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] This reaction allows for the selection of *E*- or *Z*-products.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] If an *E*-product is desired, another alternative is the Julia olefination, which uses the carbanion generated from a phenyl sulfone.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The Takai olefination based on an organochromium intermediate also delivers E-products.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] A titanium compound, Tebbe's reagent, is useful for the synthesis of methylene compounds; in this case, even esters and amides react.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] A pair of ketones or aldehydes can be deoxygenated to generate an alkene.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Symmetrical alkenes can be prepared from a single aldehyde or ketone coupling with itself, using titanium metal reduction (the McMurry reaction).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] If different ketones are to be coupled, a more complicated method is required, such as the Barton–Kellogg reaction.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] A single ketone can also be converted to the corresponding alkene via its tosylhydrazone, using sodium methoxide (the Bamford–Stevens reaction) or an alkyllithium (the Shapiro reaction).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The formation of longer alkenes via the step-wise polymerisation of smaller ones is appealing, as ethylene (the smallest alkene) is both inexpensive and readily available, with hundreds of millions of tonnes produced annually.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The Ziegler–Natta process allows for the formation of very long chains, for instance those used for polyethylene.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Where shorter chains are wanted, as they for the production of surfactants, then processes incorporating a olefin metathesis step, such as the Shell higher olefin process are important.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Olefin metathesis is also used commercially for the interconversion of ethylene and 2-butene to propylene.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Transition metal catalyzed hydrovinylation is another important alkene synthesis process starting from alkene itself.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] It involves the addition of a hydrogen and a vinyl group (or an alkenyl group) across a double bond.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Reduction of alkynes is a useful method for the stereoselective synthesis of disubstituted alkenes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Reduction of the alkyne by sodium metal in liquid ammonia gives the *trans*-alkene.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] For the preparation multisubstituted alkenes, carbometalation of alkynes can give rise to a large variety of alkene derivatives.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Alkenes can be synthesized from other alkenes via rearrangement reactions.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Besides olefin metathesis (described above), many pericyclic reactions can be used such as the ene reaction and the Cope rearrangement.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] In the Diels–Alder reaction, a cyclohexene derivative is prepared from a diene and a reactive or electron-deficient alkene.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Unsaturated hydrocarbons are widely used to produce plastics, medicines, and other useful materials.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Plants are the main natural source of alkenes in the form of terpenes.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] Many of the most vivid natural pigments are terpenes; e.g. lycopene (red in tomatoes), carotene (orange in carrots), and xanthophylls (yellow in egg yolk).
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The simplest of all alkenes, ethylene is a signaling molecule that influences the ripening of plants.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] The Curiosity rover discovered on Mars long chain alkanes with up to 12 consecutive carbon atoms.
[src:aliphatic-compound/alkene] They could be derived from either abiotic or biological sources.
